fp||cp|2|cs|1|ht|e|at|^b@2The ^*bInverted Minor Convention^*n is used over a one of a minor opening bid by partner.
There are two parts in this raise of the minor – one is a weak raise, the other constructive.   
The convention is called Inverted Minors as we reverse the meaning of the single raise and the jump raise.   
A Passed hand can still use the convention, as it can still have the constructive values.

^*bCriteria^*n - You should NOT have a 4-card Major when raising the minor.
Either 2 or 3 of the opened minor 100% denies a Major.
Using the Inverted Minor bid means you are giving up on finding a Major fit.
You must have 5+ cards in opener’s (partner's) minor suit.

^*bIn competition^*n – The ^*upreemptive jump raise^*n bid (1@d - (overcall or X) - 3@d ) is still "on",
however, the single (constructive) raise is "off" in competition.

The Inverted Minor bid needs to be ^*balerted^*n – both the 2-level club/diamond and 3-level club/diamond raises.

Discuss this fully with a regular partner before you start to use Inverted Minors and practice the full convention.

Note: The BBO GIB ROBOTS DO NOT PLAY INVERTED MINORS FULLY – They only play the 2 OR 3 level bids, but apparently don't know the rest of the convention.

