mn|The constructive raise|cp|2|at|^b@2

The Constructive raise:    1@c - 2@c    or     1@d - 2@d

Both 2@c and 2@d are FORCING bids (but not necessarily game forcing).

The Constructive raise (10+ HCP) DENIES a 4-card Major.

Question:  Should you count only High Card Points (HCP) or Dummy points as well, and why?
Answer:  When you make a 1@c - 2@c bid, you don’t really want to play in @cs.
You really want to play in NT – so points should be only HCP!
Count points as though you are going to play in NT.

Where the "weak" raise is still "on" in competition, the "constructive raise" is NOT.

With a good hand after interference you ^*bcue bid^*n the opponent's suit to show support and game interest.


What happens next after a  1@c - 2@c    or     1@d - 2@d   raise?|
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


at|

A STOPPER bidding sequence starts.  Both partners show their stoppers for NT.

Stoppers are: A  KQ  Kx (a poor stopper and better to consider it half a stopper)  Kxx  QJx  JTxx.
Qxx or QT are NOT full stoppers.
A VOID is never a stopper!

You do not have to alert stopper-showing bids.

(In a later section "half stoppers" will be discussed, also part of the IM convention)


