mn|The constructive raise   Key Points|cp|2|at|^b@2

KEY POINTS:

The OBJECTIVE with Inverted Minors (IM) is to play in NT if possible.
Having a strong minor suit fit (8-9+ cards in the suit) and stoppers in all the other suits suggests a NT contract.

When you use IM, you should NOT have a 4-card Major and you DO have a 5-card fit for opener’s minor suit.

Using the Inverted Minors convention is a request to start showing stoppers for NT.

The suit stopper sequence of bids ensures you have all suits stopped before you choose a NT contract.
Discovering a suit is not stopped means you return to the opening minor suit and play in it (@c's or @d's).

During the stopper sequence of bids, the first person who knows that a suit has no stopper held by either partner 
bids the lowest level in the agreed minor suit.

The first person who knows all suits are stopped bids NT at the appropriate level based on HCP.
If necessary, the other person can continue to game with enough HCP.


After an overcall:

If the opponents overcall, the single raise of Inverted Minors is off, but the preemptive jump raise is still used.

With a good hand, the stopper bidding sequence is not necessary after an overcall, 
since the opponents have announced the dangerous suit.
If you have stoppers in the overcalled suit, you can still consider NT.
If you don't, bid the minor suit again.


